        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer266256236" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5991151468196149546">This architecture classic from 1977 approaches architecture in a way that&apos;s altogether new to me: it provides 253 archetypal elements of design that together form a &quot;language&quot; to speak of an infinite variety of designs, from the large scale (regional metro plans) to the small scale (individual homes). <br/><br/>I loved how this book was very easy to pick up and put down--the 1000 or so pages don&apos;t have to be read all at one go for it to make sense.<br/><br/>What I hate about this book: I adore the building plans Al</span>
  <span id="freeText5991151468196149546" style="display:none">This architecture classic from 1977 approaches architecture in a way that's altogether new to me: it provides 253 archetypal elements of design that together form a "language" to speak of an infinite variety of designs, from the large scale (regional metro plans) to the small scale (individual homes). <br /><br />I loved how this book was very easy to pick up and put down--the 1000 or so pages don't have to be read all at one go for it to make sense.<br /><br />What I hate about this book: I adore the building plans Alexander proposes in A Pattern Language, and I can't read a single pattern without being wistful about the gap between what could be (as proposed in his book) and what the architecture in the world I actually live in looks like. I'd rather live in his world!</span>
  <a data-text-id="5991151468196149546" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

