<div id="review_2325804369" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2325804369" />
    <a title="Alexandra Cross" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/79282337-alexandra-cross"><img alt="Alexandra Cross" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1521250725p2/79282337.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2325804369?book_show_action=true">Apr 29, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Alexandra Cross" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Alexandra Cross" href="/user/show/79282337-alexandra-cross">Alexandra Cross</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2325804369" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6363969237237556913">This book changed my outlook on my environment and made me more cautious of that &apos;why do I feel cozier, more comfortable here but not there&apos; awareness. <br/><br/>I was able to download a free copy of this book to my phone. It&apos;s a long book, over one thousand pages, but it&apos;s split into 3-10 page topics so it&apos;s easy to pick up and read. I did this as an alternative to scrolling through social media. Good fix.<br/><br/>I heard of A Pattern Language from a Tim Ferris episode with Gretchen Rubin. <br/><br/>Anyway, this book is re</span>
  <span id="freeText6363969237237556913" style="display:none">This book changed my outlook on my environment and made me more cautious of that 'why do I feel cozier, more comfortable here but not there' awareness. <br /><br />I was able to download a free copy of this book to my phone. It's a long book, over one thousand pages, but it's split into 3-10 page topics so it's easy to pick up and read. I did this as an alternative to scrolling through social media. Good fix.<br /><br />I heard of A Pattern Language from a Tim Ferris episode with Gretchen Rubin. <br /><br />Anyway, this book is really just full of quirky and fascinating ways humans enjoy their environment. Part one is buildings, roads, environments. Part two is homes and interiors. Part three is building (I skipped the last chunk since it wasn't something I think I could retain). <br /><br />Things that stuck with me:<br /><br />1. A building shouldn't be a long stretch, you should be able to pass by it within a few moments. Keeps the walking from becoming boring.<br />2. Roads should be winding. It's daunting otherwise.<br />3. No one wants to walk near busy, loud highways. Think of parking spaces surrounding buildings as an island of pavement.<br />4. We feel more comfortable with light on both sides of the room.<br />5. Granny flats or cottages for grandparents/teens are a good idea.<br />6. Ceilings of different heights give us different feelings.<br />7. Homes should face the south and have each room on the direction of the sunrise versus sunset. Example, kitchen nook where the sunrises. <br /><br /><br />This book is great. I definitely recommend it. If not, look at homes built around his guidance. Also has made me appreciate older architecture and despise modern.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6363969237237556913" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


