    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_294495816" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/294495816" />
    <a title="Joni Baboci" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4485647-joni-baboci"><img alt="Joni Baboci" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1635418490p2/4485647.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/294495816?book_show_action=true">Mar 14, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Joni Baboci" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Joni Baboci" href="/user/show/4485647-joni-baboci">Joni Baboci</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4485647-joni-baboci?shelf=economics">economics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4485647-joni-baboci?shelf=philosophy">philosophy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4485647-joni-baboci?shelf=ecology">ecology</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4485647-joni-baboci?shelf=urbanism">urbanism</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4485647-joni-baboci?shelf=evolution">evolution</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4485647-joni-baboci?shelf=architecture">architecture</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4485647-joni-baboci?shelf=roamed">roamed</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4485647-joni-baboci?shelf=geography">geography</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4485647-joni-baboci?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4485647-joni-baboci?shelf=utopia">utopia</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer294495816" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1913158163313376046"><i>&quot;The fundamental philosophy behind the use of pattern languages is that buildings should be uniquely adapted to individual needs and sites; and that the plans of buildings should be rather loose and fluid, in order to accommodate these subtleties.&quot;</i><br/><br/><b>Introduction</b><br/><a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/79766.A_Pattern_Language_Towns__Buildings__Construction' title='A Pattern Language Towns, Buildings, Construction by Christopher Alexander' rel='nofollow noopener'>A Pattern Language: Towns, Buildings, Construction</a> is not simply a guide on how to build. It feels more like a hand guide on how to live and reconnect with what makes us human - not by shunning technology but rather by embracing it in a mor</span>
  <span id="freeText1913158163313376046" style="display:none"><i>"The fundamental philosophy behind the use of pattern languages is that buildings should be uniquely adapted to individual needs and sites; and that the plans of buildings should be rather loose and fluid, in order to accommodate these subtleties."</i><br /><br /><b>Introduction</b><br /><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/79766.A_Pattern_Language_Towns__Buildings__Construction" title="A Pattern Language Towns, Buildings, Construction by Christopher Alexander" rel="nofollow noopener">A Pattern Language: Towns, Buildings, Construction</a> is not simply a guide on how to build. It feels more like a hand guide on how to live and reconnect with what makes us human - not by shunning technology but rather by embracing it in a more personal and relatable way. This book concerns architecture and construction as much as it concerns ideology, politics, planning, urbanism, psychology, sociology and most importantly human relationships. It expounds a compelling romantic notion of a democratic commune grounded on ecology with communist economic elements and humanity as its driving cause. <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/45359.Christopher_Alexander" title="Christopher Alexander" rel="nofollow noopener">Christopher Alexander</a> is clear that not everything will work and that some of the patterns are far-fetched, yet the book is courageous in that it doesn't compromise. The patterns are out there and if you want to use just a few of them and not concern yourself with the whole, you can; however this decision is not made by the authors in advance. For example in pattern nr. 178 "Composting": the authors suggest that sewers are not sustainable and individual dry composting of waste should be used universally. In my opinion this pattern is a bit extreme however it's a pity that basic gems like recycling grey-water and using it for flushing toilettes (and thus saving 50% of drinking water usage) still have not taken hold - even after making perfect sense for 35 years.<br /><br /><b>On building individuality</b><br />Alexander and his colleagues treat architecture like a human being. Each one is different. An updated argument can be made that humanity has given up on good design. As long as we build zero-energy carbon neutral buildings everything else will be fine. Sustainability is great but it does not equal building comfortable and human-centered environments. The two have to co-exist as long as we make an active effort to learn from the past. This book is a tome that tries to make that effort. It revolves around human sensibility and against industrializing food, construction and everything else that is meant to connect us to the world. It reminds me of Arcosanti by Soleri and it makes sense, since both entities were materialized in the ethereal free-think sensibility of the seventies.<br /><br /><b>On research</b><br />At times Alexander tries to make research-based or statistical arguments for his perfectly logical patterns yet almost every time his sample size is too small. It could be interpreted as part of his concept of small, local and humane research versus mechanized mass research. Scientific research does not work like that however. It's true that Alexander's approach to research at times feels interesting and refreshing, yet most of the time it's hard to see it as anything more than circumstantial facts added on as an afterthought to the pattern rather than a rigorous and scientific effort. For example in pattern nr. 241 "Seat Spots" the authors state: <br /><br /><i>"We made random spot checks on selected benches in Berkeley, California, and recorded these facts about each bench: Was it occupied or empty? Did it give a view of current activity or not? Was it in the sun or not? What was the current wind velocity? Three of the eleven benches were occupied; eight were empty." </i><br /><br />The idea is awesome, however a random sample of 11 benches to illustrate the concept definitely doesn't feel enough, even though the basic argument is perfectly logical.<br /><br />On the other hand it's amazing to see the names of the research papers cited. Original, extremely interesting and plain fun research that just doesn't happen anymore. I'll cite some examples:<br /><br />Tyrus Porter, <b>A Study of Path Choosing Behavior</b>, thesis, University of California, Berkeley, 1964<br />"Children's Images of Houses: A Prolegomena to the <b>Study of Why People Still Want Pitched Roofs</b>,"<br />"<b>Conference Behavior</b>," Columbia University Forum, Summer, 1967, pp. 20-25<br />L. E. White, "<b>The Outdoor Play of Children Living in Flats</b>," Living in Towns, Leo Kuper, ed., London<br /><br /><b>On the structure and style of the book</b><br />This is not a book that is supposed to be read cover to cover in one sitting. It makes much more sense to read the book according to the specific needs of your project and using the introductory chapter as a guide through the language, nevertheless I felt like a read-through primes you for future use! Differently from most theoretical treatises on architecture, A Pattern Language takes a much more direct and practical approach. It doesn't just expose a theory of how something might theoretically be, but rather a set of instructions of how it can be built.<br /><br />Contrary to popular belief Alexander and his colleagues are not Luddites. They are not against technology, or using technology to better the human condition. Some patterns may feel like that, however the aim of each pattern seems targeted at creating an integral, understandable, comfortable and humane architecture that uses technology as a means to an end rather than an end in its own right.<br /><br />In discussing construction Alexander makes it clear from the beginning that this is the more unrefined part of the book - and it shows. It is a weird amalgam of raw statics combined with an almost hidden desire to make individuals single-handedly build four-story constructions. However some of the ideas are still valid and interesting - i.e. how foundation, walls, columns and beams should be a whole rather than a collection of parts. The book itself is also very honest:<br /><br /><i>"We believe that some kind of structure which is continuous with the ground is needed: but we quite haven't been able to work it out. Meanwhile, we state this pattern as a kind of challenge." </i><br /><br /><b>The future</b><br />It's a pity that Alexander and his team do not give themselves the benefit of future development, and only seldom try to imagine how a pattern language might apply to a future where things might be very different. We need an updated version with some research from the last decade but with the same courage and human sensibility that Alexander and his co-authors use in A Pattern Language. <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/13690365.The_Battle_for_the_Life_and_Beauty_of_the_Earth_A_Struggle_Between_Two_World_Systems" title="The Battle for the Life and Beauty of the Earth A Struggle Between Two World-Systems by Christopher Alexander" rel="nofollow noopener">The Battle for the Life and Beauty of the Earth: A Struggle Between Two World-Systems</a> - his latest book - might be exactly that...<br /><br /><b>Conclusion</b><br />It's one of the very best books I have ever read. Sure, in a few patterns it almost seems like Alexander is more concerned with making the pattern a direct opposite to a specific modernist idea rather than working on it for its own sake. This mostly happens in the part about construction and becomes a bit repetitive. I dislike that he has not given at least a short part of the book to what he might think are some of the good things that modernism brought. However it's easy to let this one pass considering what you are constantly getting from this book. How it continuously pokes your imagination and pushes you to consider and re-consider whole ideas as well as minute details of architecture in a totally different light.<br /><br />We are an adaptable species, however our willingness to adapt does not mean that architecture is currently moving in the right direction. Alexander continuously makes you ponder the question: Should architects and urbanists be blamed for the current urban condition? Is the modern city a cemetery for human sensibility? Does it kill being human? Does it transform us into efficient drones without real aims and objectives in life? Capitalism has been in crisis for a while and when (if) it fails a new organization of urban life will be needed if humanity wants to reform itself and set its priorities straight. This book seems like the perfect starting point!</span>
  <a data-text-id="1913158163313376046" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


